\end{align*}

The initial momentum of the car is:

{eq}\begin{align*}
p_i &= m \cdot u \\
&= 2400\ \text{kg} \times 26.68\ \text{m/s} \\
&= 640320\ \text{kg.m/s}
\end{align*}

After the collision, the combined mass has a final velocity of 0 m/s due to a completely inelastic collision, so the final momentum is:

{eq}\begin{align*}
p_f &= (1623\ \text{kg}) \times 0 \\
&= 0
\end{align*}

The change in momentum is:

{eq}\begin{align*}
\Delta p &= p_f - p_i \\
&= 0 - 640320\ \text{kg.m/s} \\
&= -640320\ \text{kg.m/s}
\end{align*}

The average force exerted by the target is the change in momentum divided by the time interval, which can be approximated by the thickness of the target:

{eq}\begin{align*}
F_{avg} &= \frac{-640320\ \text{kg.m/s}}{0.0115\ \text{m}} \\
&\approx -556409090.91\ \text{N}
\end{align*}

Since force is a vector quantity and the direction is opposite to the initial momentum, the magnitude of the average force is:

{eq}\begin{align*}
